Business Analytics Course Project¶

Project description

You've done beautifully in the Practicum course, and you've been offered an internship in the analytical department at Yandex.Afisha. Your first task is to help optimize marketing expenses.

Tasks

  • Study the following:
    • How people use the product
    • When they start to buy
    • How much money each customer brings
    • When they pay off
  • Use the following sources for analysis
    • Use server logs with data on Yandex.Afisha from June 2017 - May 2018
    • Dump file with all orders for the period
    • Marketing expenses statistics

Instructions for completing the project

Step 1. Download the data and prepare it for analysis

  • Store the data on visits, orders, and expenses in variables. Optimize the data for analysis. Make sure each column contains the correct data type.
  • Use the following file paths:
    • /datasets/visits_log_us.csv. Download dataset
    • /datasets/orders_log_us.csv. Download dataset
    • /datasets/costs_us.csv. Download dataset

Step 2. Make reports and calculate metrics:

  • Product
    • How many people use it every day, week, and month?
    • How many sessions are there per day? (One user might have more than one session.)
    • What is the length of each session?
    • How often do users come back?
  • Sales
    • When do people start buying? (In KPI analysis, we're usually interested in knowing the time that elapses between registration and conversion — when the user becomes a customer. For example, if registration and the first purchase occur on the same day, the user might fall into category Conversion 0d. If the first purchase happens the next day, it will be Conversion 1d. You can use any approach that lets you compare the conversions of different cohorts, so that you can determine which cohort, or marketing channel, is most effective.)
    • How many orders do they make during a given period of time?
    • What is the average purchase size?
    • How much money do they bring? (LTV)
  • Marketing
    • How much money was spent? Overall/per source/over time
    • How much did customer acquisition from each of the sources cost?
    • How worthwhile where the investments? (ROI)
    • Plot graphs to display how these metrics differ for various devices and ad sources and how they change in time.

Step 3. Write a conclusion: advise marketing experts how much money to invest and where.

  • What sources/platforms would you recommend? Back up your choice: what metrics did you focus on? Why? What conclusions did you draw after finding the metric values?

Description of the data

  • The visits table (server logs with data on website visits):
    • Uid — user's unique identifier
    • Device — user's device
    • Start Ts — session start date and time
    • End Ts — session end date and time
      • All dates in this table are in YYYY-MM-DD format.
    • Source Id — identifier of the ad source the user came from
  • The orders table (data on orders):
    • Uid — unique identifier of the user making an order
    • Buy Ts — order date and time
    • Revenue — Yandex.Afisha's revenue from the order
  • The costs table (data on marketing expenses):
    • source_id — ad source identifier
    • dt — date
    • costs — expenses on this ad source on this day

Plan of Action

    1. Open the data files and study the general information
    1. Data Preprocessing
      • Create working versions of the dataframes

    1. Analyze the data
      • Answer the requested information

4b Sales Data Analysis¶

Examine the user purchase activity

  • Sales
    • When do people start buying? (In KPI analysis, we're usually interested in knowing the time that elapses between registration and conversion — when the user becomes a customer. For example, if registration and the first purchase occur on the same day, the user might fall into category Conversion 0d. If the first purchase happens the next day, it will be Conversion 1d. You can use any approach that lets you compare the conversions of different cohorts, so that you can determine which cohort, or marketing channel, is most effective.)
      • find first session date
      • find first order date
      • calculate the conversion day - ie when a user becomes a buyer
      • evaluate the conversion day information
    • How many orders do they make during a given period of time?
      • create necessary columns
      • create a series with the number of orders per unique user for each month
      • determine average weekly orders
    • What is the average purchase size?
      • calculate the average revenue per order
    • How much money do they bring? (LTV)
      • LTV (lifetime value) is the customer's lifetime value.
      • It's the total amount of money a customer brings to the company on average by making purchases.
      • When calculating LTV, analysts usually consider the gross profit from a customer per period.
        • create necessary columns and tables
        • create cohorts based on first session month
        • calculate the revenue per cohort
        • calculate the age of the cohort = difference between the first session and first order
        • calcultae the LTV
        • create a heat map for analysis

How much money do they bring? (LTV)

  • LTV (lifetime value) is the customer's lifetime value.
  • It's the total amount of money a customer brings to the company on average by making purchases.
  • When calculating LTV, analysts usually consider the gross profit from a customer per period.
    • create necessary columns and tables
    • create cohorts based on first session month
    • calculate the revenue per cohort
    • calculate the age of the cohort = difference between the first session and first order
    • calcultae the LTV
    • create a heat map for analysis

4b Sales Data Analysis Conclusions¶

When do people start buying? (In KPI analysis, we're usually interested in knowing the time that elapses between registration and conversion — when the user becomes a customer. For example, if registration and the first purchase occur on the same day, the user might fall into category Conversion 0d. If the first purchase happens the next day, it will be Conversion 1d. You can use any approach that lets you compare the conversions of different cohorts, so that you can determine which cohort, or marketing channel, is most effective.)

  • Actions performed
    • created series to get first session and order information
    • combined tables
    • calculated the conversion day - when a user becamea buyer
    • evaluated the stats and made a histogram
  • Conclusions
    • 50% of conversions (user to a buyer) happen by day 0 of a users first session date
    • 75% of conversions happen by day 2
    • This suggests that most users become buyers soon after their first visit

How many orders do they make during a given period of time?

  • Actions performed
    • created necessary columns
    • created a series with the number of orders per unique user for each month
    • determined average weekly orders
  • Conclusions
    • 1.21 average number of orders placed per user per month

What is the average purchase size?

  • Actions performed
    • calculated the average revenue per order
  • Conclusions
    • 5 dollars is the average purchase size per order

How much money do they bring? (LTV)

  • Actions performed
    • created columns with the first session and order month in the conversion_table and orders tables respectively
    • created a new dataframe with first session information
    • merged the two to create information on the first session and orders
    • created a new series to create cohorts based on first session month and to calculate the number of users per cohort (size)
    • created a new series to calculate the revenue of each cohort
    • created a cohort age column
    • merged the cohort size and revenue/age tables
    • calculated the LTV and created a heat map or the cumulative LTV for analysis
  • Conclusions
    • There appears to be a pattern that happens every 3 months, where those cohorts bring in more value
      • This is happening for the June, September, and December cohorts
      • In these cohorts LTV doubles after about 5 months
      • For the other cohorts, this transition is slower (> 10 months)

How much money was spent overtime

  • Actions Performed
  • calculated total marketing costs
    • 329,131.62 was spent on marketing

How much money was spent per ad source?

  • Actions Performed
    • created a new series to calculate the cost per ad source
    • evaluated the cost per ad source stats
    • created a graph of the cost per ad source
  • Conclusions
    • There are 7 different ad sources in this data set
    • The average cost per ad source is 47018 dollars, this is high due to the max costs
    • yearly cost ranges from 5517 - 141321 dollars
    • 75% of ad costs were 56415 or less

How much money was spent over time?

  • Actions Performed
    • created a new column for the month the ad was purchased
    • created a new series to calculate the cost of ads per month
    • evaluated the stats of the cost of ads per month
    • created a graph of the costs of ads per month
  • Conclusions
    • the least amount spent on ads was in August: 14790, the most in December: 38315
    • the average cost per month is 27427, this is very close to the median of 27392, suggesting the data is close to a relative distribution

How much did cusotmer acquisition from each of the sources cost?

  • Actions Performed
    • Calculate the CAC - (customer acquisition cost) is the cost of attracting a customer—the money a new customer costs a company
  • Conclusions
    • created a series to calculate the number of unique users per ad source
    • combined cost_per_source table and user_per_source table to calculat the CAC
    • evaluated the stats of the cost of acquisition
    • created a graph of the ad cost per customer acquisition
      • the cost of acquisition ranges from 0.59 - 1.89 dollars
      • 75% of cost acquisition costs 1.36 dollars or less
        • compared to the revenue brought in during the first month for each cohort this is very good (the revenue ranges from 4.47 - 13.69, with 75% bringing in 4.82 or more dollars in their first month)

How worthwhile where the investments? (ROI)

  • Actions Performed
    • created a new series to calculate the revenue from each cohort
    • calculated the ROMI by dividing the each cohort's revenue by the ad costs per month
    • created a graph of the ROMI
  • Conclusions
    • 5 and almost 6 cohorts had a 100% return on investment, so about 50% of this data set had a return on investment
    • cohorts that had 100% or more ROMI = 2017: June, Sept, Oct, Nov, Dec, 2018: Jan (nearly)
